'''George Lee''' (born 27 September 1962)<ref name=IT_20090509>
{{cite news
|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/weekend/2009/0509/1224246181570.html
|title=From goggle box to ballot box
|author=Deagl<U+00E1>n De Br<U+00E9>ad<U+00FA>n
|date=9 May 2009
|newspaper=[[The Irish Times]]
|publisher=Irish Times Trust
|archiveurl = http://www.webcitation.org/5nW3bfprD
|archivedate= 13 February 2010
|accessdate=10 May 2009
}}</ref> is an [[Irish people|Irish]] economist, journalist and former [[Fine Gael]] politician. He worked for [[Raidi<U+00F3> Teilif<U+00ED>s <U+00C9>ireann|RT<U+00C9>]] from 1992 to 2009. He was appointed Economics Editor in 1996. During his time in [[RT<U+00C9> News and Current Affairs]] he was named Irish Journalist of the Year for uncovering a major [[Tax avoidance and tax evasion|tax evasion]] and overcharging scandal at [[National Irish Bank]]. He has also presented many documentary programmes for RT<U+00C9>.

Lee became a [[Teachta D<U+00E1>la]] (TD) for the [[Dublin South (D<U+00E1>il <U+00C9>ireann constituency)|Dublin South]] constituency in June 2009, winning a [[Dublin South by-election, 2009|by-election]] with a 53.4% majority and was referred to as a "celebrity TD". On 8 February 2010 Lee announced his resignation both from Fine Gael and from [[D<U+00E1>il <U+00C9>ireann]], having spent nine months in politics. His reasoning was that he had "virtually no influence or input". He is set to return to RT<U+00C9> later in 2010.

==Early and personal life==
Lee's father was a motor mechanic and his mother was a hairdresser.<ref name=II_20100209>
{{cite news
|url=http://www.independent.ie/national-news/he-didnt-make-friends-and-looked-down-on-us-2054213.html
|title='He didn't make friends and looked down on us'
|author=Aine Kerr
|newspaper=[[Irish Independent]]
|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]
|date=9 February 2010
|accessdate=13 February 2010
}}</ref> Lee was the seventh in a family of eight children and grew up in [[Templeogue]], [[Dublin]].<ref name="RT<U+00C9> Guide 2008">
{{cite web
|url=http://www.rteguide.ie/2008/0120/staroftheday.html
|title=RT<U+00C9> article on George Lee in China
|work=[[RT<U+00C9> Guide]]
|publisher=[[RT<U+00C9> Commercial Enterprises Ltd]]
|date=20 January 2008
|accessdate=21 February 2009
}}</ref> He attended [[Col<U+00E1>iste <U+00C9>anna]], a Christian Brothers' School in the Dublin suburb of [[Ballyroan, County Dublin|Ballyroan]]. Lee is a graduate of [[University College Dublin]] and holds an [[Master of Science|MSc]] in Economics from the [[London School of Economics]] where his specialist area was labour economics and unemployment.

He is married to Mary Lee (n<U+00E9>e Kitson),<ref name="IT_20100223">
{{cite news
|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2010/0223/1224265037360.html
|title=Crowd-puller of messianic proportions takes to pulpit to spread his message
|author=Michael Parsons
|date=23 February 2010
|work=[[The Irish Times]]
|publisher=Irish Times Trust
|quote=His wife, Mary (nee Kitson) is a native of Borrisokane, Co Tipperary.
|accessdate=23 February 2010
}}</ref> they have two children, Alison and Harry,<ref name="RT<U+00C9> Guide 2008" /> and lives in [[Cabinteely]]. Lee famously travelled to work in RT<U+00C9> via [[Segway PT|Segway]],<ref name=IT_20090509/> once giving it a test ride live on ''[[Tubridy Tonight]]''.<ref>
{{cite web
|url=http://www.rte.ie/tv/tubridytonight/20090321.html
|title=Tubridy Tonight
|work=[[RT<U+00C9>]]
|date=21 March 2009
