===Political career===
[[File:Politicians at Lisbon 2.jpg|thumb|Lee (right) with [[Eamon Ryan]] (left) and [[D<U+00E9>irdre de B<U+00FA>rca]] (centre) at the [[Twenty-eighth Amendment of the Constitution of Ireland|second Lisbon Treaty referendum]].]]
On 5 May 2009 on the ''[[RT<U+00C9> News at One|News at One]]'' on [[RT<U+00C9> Radio 1]], Lee announced that he was resigning as Economic Editor with RT<U+00C9> and announced his intention to seek the [[Fine Gael]] nomination for the [[Dublin South (D<U+00E1>il <U+00C9>ireann constituency)|Dublin South]] [[Dublin South by-election, 2009|by-election]] in 2009.<ref name=RTE_20090505>
{{cite news
|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2009/0505/finegael.html
|title=RT<U+00C9>'s Lee to stand for FG in Dublin South
|work=[[RT<U+00C9> News]]
|date=5 May 2009
|accessdate=5 May 2009
}}</ref> Lee took a years unpaid leave from RT<U+00C9> in May 2009.<ref>
{{cite news
|url=http://www.independent.ie/national-news/exrte-editor-to-get-full-salary-if-he-returns-2054256.html
|title=Ex-RT<U+00C9> editor to get full salary if he returns
|work=[[RT<U+00C9> News]]
|date=9 February 2010
|accessdate=9 February 2010
}}</ref> On 6 May 2009, Lee was chosen as the Fine Gael candidate for the by-election. He was the only candidate for the nomination.<ref name=RTE_20090506>
{{cite news
|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2009/0506/election.html
|title=Parties select bye-election candidates
|work=[[RT<U+00C9> News]]
|date=6 May 2009
|accessdate=7 May 2009
}}</ref>

He was elected on the first count to represent Dublin South on 6 June 2009. He received over 53% of the 1st preference vote. In total he received 27,768 1st preference votes.<ref name=elecs_irl>
