|work=Irish Software Developers Network
|accessdate=13 February 2010}}
</ref>

===Resignation from politics===
On 8 February 2010, he announced his resignation from Fine Gael and from D<U+00E1>il <U+00C9>ireann, due to having "virtually no influence or input" into shaping Fine Gael's economic policies at a time of economic upheaval.<ref name="RT<U+00C9> Fine Gael TD George Lee resigns">
{{cite news
|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2010/0208/leeg.html
|title=Fine Gael TD George Lee resigns
|work=[[RT<U+00C9> News]]
|date=8 February 2010
|accessdate=8 February 2010
}}</ref><ref>
{{cite news
|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/breaking/2010/0208/breaking40.htm
|title=George Lee resigns from Fine Gael and D<U+00E1>il <U+00C9>ireann
|newspaper=[[The Irish Times]]
|publisher=Irish Times Trust
|date=8 February 2010
|archiveurl= http://www.webcitation.org/5nXUMKeIZ
|archivedate= 14 February 2010
|accessdate=8 February 2010
}}</ref> It emerged that on 2 February, Lee met with the Fine Gael leader, [[Enda Kenny]] and told him of his intention to resign. Kenny then offered Lee the frontbench position as spokesman on economic planning. Speaking to reporters outside [[Leinster House]] soon after his announcement, Lee said it would have been dishonest of him to accept the position: "I had absolutely no input for nine months. I think I had to be honest with myself and honest with the electorate about that and not pretend." Asked if his resignation was a vote of no confidence in Kenny, Lee said there were "certainly lots of large mutterings at the moment in relation to the leader's position". He said he had "minimal involvement" with Fine Gael finance spokesman [[Richard Bruton]]. "I had a maximum of two or three conversations with Richard Bruton in a total nine months period. I don<U+2019>t know how my relationship is with [him]" Lee said.<ref name=IT_20090209>
{{cite news
|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2010/0209/1224264030191.html
|title=Lee rejected Kenny offer of job on front bench
|author=Harry McGee
|newspaper=[[The Irish Times]]
|publisher=Irish Times Trust
|date=9 February 2010
|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5nXUSVKH5
|archivedate=14 February 2010
|accessdate=9 February 2010
}}</ref> 

Kenny noted Lee had been appointed chair of the party's committee on economic policy and also its forum. "I had anticipated a very important role for [George Lee] in the coming period with Fine Gael." Kenny's spokesman later dismissed the proposition that the resignation had implications for his leadership. He cited the public endorsement of Kenny by 20 D<U+00E1>il deputies over the course of the weekend.<ref name=IT_20090209/> Former Fine Gael leader [[Michael Noonan]] said he was surprised at the decision: "I thought that George Lee was fitting in well", adding that he believed he would have been a cabinet member in a Fine Gael led government.

George Lee was criticised after his resignation by Senator [[Eoghan Harris]], who was speaking on the ''Lunchtime'' programme of [[Newstalk]] Radio. Harris suggested financial considerations and long working hours of politicians were the reasons why Lee resigned.<ref>{{cite video
|people=[[Eoghan Harris]], Eamon Keane
|date=10 February 2010
|title=Eoghan Harris on George Lee, Enda Kenny, and what it means to be a leader
|url=http://media.newstalk.ie/extra/473/popup
|medium=Radio broadcast
|publisher=[[Newstalk]]
|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5nW38udjw
|archivedate=13 February 2010
|accessdate=13 February 2010
}}</ref><ref>
{{cite news
|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2010/0213/1224264353785.html
|title=Miriam Lord's Week
|author=Miriam Lord
|date=13 February 2010
|newspaper=[[The Irish Times]]
|publisher=Irish Times Trust
|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5nXUYadCk
|archivedate=14 February 2010
|accessdate=13 February 2010}}
</ref> Fine Gael TD [[Brian Hayes (politician)|Brian Hayes]], who was Lee's campaign manager in the Dublin South by-election, said that in discussions with Lee, the latter had complained about "a major reduction in his income" since leaving RT<U+00C9> to become a D<U+00E1>il backbencher. Lee denied that financial considerations had anything to do with his decision to quit politics.<ref name=IT_20090211>
{{cite news
|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2010/0211/1224264202736.html
|title=Departure of Lee now in the past, says Kenny
|author=Deagl<U+00E1>n de Br<U+00E9>ad<U+00FA>n
|newspaper=[[The Irish Times]]
|publisher=Irish Times Trust
|date=11 February 2010
|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5nXUf5tT9
|archivedate=14 February 2010
|accessdate=12 February 2010
}}</ref>

RT<U+00C9> received a letter from Lee confirming his intentions to return after his leave of absence.<ref name="RT<U+00C9> gets letter confirming former TD's return">
{{cite news
|url=http://www.independent.ie/national-news/rte-gets-letter-confirming-former-tds-return-2060363.html
|title=RT<U+00C9> gets letter confirming former TD's return
|author=Jason O'Brien
|date=12 February 2010
|newspaper=[[Irish Independent]]
|publisher=[[Independent News & Media]]
|accessdate=21 February 2010
}}</ref> The ''[[Sunday Tribune]]'' said on 14 February 2010 that he will have to wait for three months before returning to RT<U+00C9>.<ref name="Sunday Trib 20100214 1" />

